If the Lagrangian does not depend on time explicitly, then the Euler-Lagrange equations admit an integral of motion called the //Energy://
$$\begin{aligned}
E(x,\dot{x})
&= \sum_{k=1}^n \dot{x}_k \fracpartial{L(x,\dot{x})}{\dot{x}_k} - L(x,\dot{x}) \\
&= \lang \dot{x},\grad_{\dot{x}} L(x,\dot{x}) \rang - L(x,\dot{x}).
\end{aligned}$$